<article>
    <h1>Bukit Timah</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201206/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-06"><time>2020-12-06</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>DU­RA­TION AND DIF­FI­CULTY</p>
    <p>One hour and 40 min­utes, about 6,600 steps with two bus rides (four to six stops each). Mod­er­ately easy walk.</p>
    <p>HIGH­LIGHTS</p>
    <p>For­mer Ford Fac­tory; Beauty World Cen­tre; For­mer Bukit Timah Rail­way Sta­tion; Masjid Al-Huda and Hoon San Tem­ple</p>
    <p>THE GOOD</p>
    <p>The For­mer Bukit Timah Rail­way Sta­tion was, for me, the high­light of this trail. It is the only sub­ur­ban sta­tion left stand­ing of the Sin­ga­pore to Bukit Timah sec­tion of the Sin­ga­pore-Kranji Rail­way, which opened in 1903.</p>
    <p>Though di­lap­i­dated, it pos­sesses a rus­tic charm. One can peer through the fence into the lit­tle cot­tage-like sta­tion or walk the weed-strewn rails.</p>
    <p>The For­mer Ford Fac­tory, where the Bri­tish sur­ren­dered Sin­ga­pore to the Ja­panese dur­ing World War II, is an in­trigu­ing wartime mu­seum that mer­its a visit on its own, ideally when one</p>
    <p>of the guided tours is on.</p>
    <p>THE BAD</p>
    <p>This is an ex­tremely elon­gated trail with lit­tle to show for it. I com­bined two of the trails, WWII Legacy and Kam­pong Life, be­gin­ning at Fuy­ong Es­tate near The Rail Mall (not rec­om­mended, would skip) and end­ing at Masjid Al-Huda and Hoon San Tem­ple near Sixth Av­enue.</p>
    <p>I left out the third, Learn­ing And</p>
    <p>Leisure, around the Botanic Gar­dens and Adam Road Food Cen­tre area – places which lots of peo­ple visit any­way for other rea­sons.</p>
    <p>Some land­marks are more than half an hour apart on foot. While it is pleas­ant to walk through the leafy en­vi­rons of the Bukit Timah Na­ture Re­serve, the route af­ter Beauty World winds tor­tu­ously past sev­eral con­struc­tion sites. Even­tu­ally I gave up and took the bus twice.</p>
    <p>Olivia Ho</p>

